<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1514,1970]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,461,1802,1827]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Variability of size in females— 
<number box="[829,935,1802,1826]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="14.700000000000001" valueMax="16.1" valueMin="13.3">13.3–16.1</number>
x 
<quantity box="[965,1105,1802,1826]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="5.8" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.1">5.1–6.5 mm</quantity>
; males— 
<number box="[1213,1321,1802,1826]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="12.65" valueMax="13.4" valueMin="11.9">11.9–13.4</number>
x 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="4.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="5.4" valueMin="4.6">4.6–5.4 mm</quantity>
. This species can easily be separated from the other 
<taxonomicName box="[788,876,1840,1863]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Deretus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[788,876,1840,1863]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Deretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by its extremely elongate spine-like anterior pronotal corners (
<figureCitation box="[399,480,1874,1898]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1753,1776]" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Pronotum, dorsal view. 13. Deretus bezdeki sp. nov. (paratype), male; 14. D. denticollis Gahan, 1900, male; 15. D. hulai sp. nov. (paratype), female; 16. D. maderai sp. nov. (holotype), male; 17. Deretus necopinatus sp. nov. (paratype), male; 18. D. spinicollis Schawaller, 2004, male." pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
Fig. 
<number box="[452,480,1874,1898]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
) and, usually, by its larger size. 
<taxonomicName box="[848,968,1875,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Deretus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bezdeki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[848,968,1875,1899]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">D. bezdeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[975,1073,1875,1899]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[975,1067,1875,1899]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
which also possesses spine-like anterior pronotal corners, is much smaller and has large acute teeth on the sides of the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1318,1910,1934]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1753,1776]" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. Pronotum, dorsal view. 13. Deretus bezdeki sp. nov. (paratype), male; 14. D. denticollis Gahan, 1900, male; 15. D. hulai sp. nov. (paratype), female; 16. D. maderai sp. nov. (holotype), male; 17. Deretus necopinatus sp. nov. (paratype), male; 18. D. spinicollis Schawaller, 2004, male." pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
Fig. 
<number box="[1289,1318,1910,1934]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
) and large tubercles on the elytra.
</paragraph>
